            "type": "paragraph",
            "content": "TILE ROOFING - Best for: Long-term homeownership (15+ years), luxury or traditional Southwestern home styles, HOA communities requiring tile (most Gladden Farms, Continental Ranch sections), maximum longevity priority, and willingness to invest more upfront for lifecycle value. Advantages: Longest lifespan (40-55 years for tiles, 25-35 years before underlayment replacement) providing superior lifecycle value, exceptional wind resistance (tiles rated 170+ mph when mechanically fastened), superior fire protection (Class A rating with non-combustible material), cool roof options readily available (reflective colors reducing cooling 15-25%), high-end appearance enhancing curb appeal and resale value, low maintenance (occasional cracked tile replacement only), and excellent hail resistance (concrete/clay won't dent like shingles). Disadvantages: Higher initial cost ($50,000-65,000 for typical Marana 2,800 sq ft home vs. $28,000-38,000 shingle), heavier weight requiring proper structural support (older homes may need reinforcement), longer installation timeline (4-6 days vs. 2-3 for shingles), individual tile replacement complexity requiring professional service, and limited color selection (earth tones, no blues/greens/grays). Best tile type for Marana: Concrete S-tile in light colors (terra cotta, adobe tan, mission clay) balances authentic Southwestern appearance, cool roof energy efficiency (SRI 70-95), and moderate cost ($45,000-55,000 installed). Clay tiles premium option for maximum longevity and prestige ($58,000-72,000)."
